00:03:41.206 --> 00:03:42.580
Well, the first
day that you came

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:44.170
here, the first
Monday you came here,

00:03:44.170 --> 00:03:46.490
you heard all about how
little we can actually

00:03:46.490 --> 00:03:47.430
even define life.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:49.171
And the reason for
that lecture is

00:03:49.171 --> 00:03:51.170
that if we're going to
find life somewhere else,

00:03:51.170 --> 00:03:53.620
we should know what
we're looking for.

00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:56.610
And you heard that lecture,
and basically, it's hopeless.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:59.960
But we are trying.

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:03.640
The second lecture went the
step of how do you actually

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:05.560
create life from chemistry.

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:08.100
So Donte Loretta pointed
out that the elements that

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:11.470
are required to create life were
not created at the Big Bang,

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:14.330
they were created when
the stars were formed.

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:17.240
And as the stars die, the
whole interstellar medium

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:22.140
becomes full of these elements,
like carbon and phosphorus

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:25.600
and nitrogen, which are
required to make DNA and so on.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:28.240
So he tried to address
the question of,

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:31.100
how do you go from
chemistry to life?

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:33.150
And he was able to
at least address,

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:37.040
in some ways, how you get the
chemistry to maybe RNA or DNA.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:39.350
And there's still the challenge
of how you make cells.

00:04:39.350 --> 00:04:41.180
He didn't even go there.

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:44.920
Today, we're going to talk
about another mystery.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:48.070
And that mystery is, how do
we get all of the biodiversity

00:04:48.070 --> 00:04:52.200
that we have in a place like the
Earth from the simple building

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:55.270
blocks that we're
all made out of.

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:57.550
So Brian Enquist
will tell us today

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:01.090
about biodiversity, how it
starts, what keeps it going,

00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:04.430
and the scaling laws in biology.

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:09.580
How do we scale up from a very
small animal to a very large

00:05:09.580 --> 00:05:11.380
animal or plant?

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:15.020
So the idea of biodiversity,
how we make all

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:17.790
that we see from
the stuff that's

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:20.710
Donte Loretta was telling
us about last time

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:22.510
is an amazing mystery.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:27.000
Now, Brian is an amazing
individual from the National

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:27.880
Science Foundation.

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:29.890
He's a Young Principal
Investigator Award.

00:05:29.890 --> 00:05:31.540
These are very important things.

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:33.340
From the Ecological
Society of America,

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.320
he got one of the most
prestigious awards

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:37.200
as a young scientist.

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:42.950
And more importantly, Popular
Mechanics, of all places,

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:46.970
named him one of the 10 most
interesting young scientists

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:47.800
to follow.

00:05:47.800 --> 00:05:49.650
So there you go, he
may have something

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:50.800
to do with cars as well.

00:05:54.590 --> 00:05:56.160
So I leave you
with Brian Enquist.

