For not only being our leader
in the College of Science

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:36.270
but also setting a good example
for what science should be,

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:39.100
not only in a real democracy,
but its role to play

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:41.480
in terms of creating dialogue.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:43.150
Unlike most of the
other speakers,

00:06:43.150 --> 00:06:45.280
I'm actually tweeting this,
so feel free to send me

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:47.310
a tweet if you want.

00:06:47.310 --> 00:06:51.250
I'll try not to tweet
while I'm talking.

00:06:51.250 --> 00:06:53.230
So what I want to
start with today

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:56.340
is actually one of my
favorite photos of the earth.

00:06:56.340 --> 00:06:59.130
This was taken in
1968 by the crew

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:01.040
of one of the Apollo missions.

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:06.610
This was the first image a
human actually saw of the earth.

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:10.890
So this is the first photograph
of the Earth taken by a human.

00:07:10.890 --> 00:07:17.170
And what's amazing is that
I don't study the universe.

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.480
I don't build a satellite.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:21.000
I study life on Earth.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:22.690
And so what I would
like to do today

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:26.310
is tell you a little bit
about life on Earth but also

00:07:26.310 --> 00:07:29.410
what I find absolutely
amazing about life on Earth.

00:07:29.410 --> 00:07:32.430
So let me show you one of
the places that we work.

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:40.210
This is the Kosnipata
Valley, this is in Peru.

00:07:40.210 --> 00:07:42.650
It's right near
Manu National Park.

00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:47.160
It's perhaps the most
biodiverse place on the planet.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:51.090
We study the diversity
of plants and trees

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:52.440
along an elevational gradient.

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:55.060
So we go from tree line
at the top of the Andes,

00:07:55.060 --> 00:07:58.480
we drop all the way down
to the Amazon basin.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:02.060
And we want to understand what
not only controls the changes

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:04.030
in diversity that we see
along these gradients

00:08:04.030 --> 00:08:08.464
but also how tropical
forests, how ecosystems work.

00:08:08.464 --> 00:08:09.880
And we also want
to understand how

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:11.790
these organisms work,
in particular how

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.400
these trees work.

00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:16.890
So when we go out on our various
different collecting missions,

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:24.260
we sample leaves, we climb
trees, we bring them down.

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:26.700
And we put them in these
pretty fancy bits of equipment

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.410
here, where we're actually
measuring their metabolism,

00:08:29.410 --> 00:08:31.360
their photosynthetic rate.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:34.140
We then take the
leaves, we process them

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:37.610
here in a field lab in the
middle of the rainforest.

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:39.214
Take those leaves,
we bundle them up,

00:08:39.214 --> 00:08:41.380
and we bring them back to
the University of Arizona,

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:43.919
where we measure other
aspects of their metabolism,

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:46.755
such as nitrogen
content, phosphorus

00:08:46.755 --> 00:08:52.400
content, isotopic various
signatures and so on.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:53.990
And our ultimate
goal here is that we

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:58.330
want to understand how these
trees, these organisms, work.

00:08:58.330 --> 00:09:01.890
But ultimately, we want to
understand how these ecosystems

00:09:01.890 --> 00:09:03.960
will respond to climate change.

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:06.210
But we don't want
to understand how

00:09:06.210 --> 00:09:09.470
they change over time
or across elevation,

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:11.600
but we want to be
able to predict what's

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:13.162
going to happen in the future.

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:19.220
Now, to try to bring in
the predictive sense,

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:22.650
we also work quite a bit on
developing mathematical theory.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:25.640
And a lot of this math
is aimed to ultimately

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:28.200
boil down and kind of
get at these measurements

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.740
that we're taking
within the field

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:32.490
and take then, those
measurements in order

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:34.960
to scale up and
understand and make

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:37.880
predictions about how
these tropical forests work

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:39.863
but also how ecosystems work.

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:46.900
So this is really a search.

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:49.570
We're interested in
searching for generalities

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:50.970
in how life works.

00:09:50.970 --> 00:09:55.450
We want to understand something
as vast as the Amazon ring

00:09:55.450 --> 00:10:01.530
forest, which also you can think
of as the lung of our planet.

00:10:01.530 --> 00:10:04.210
What happens in the Amazon
influences are global climate,

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:07.620
it influences the
rest of the biosphere.

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:11.430
So what can we do in order
then, to search for generalities

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:15.690
or rules about how organisms
work, how diversity responds

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:19.530
to changing climates, in
order to ultimately provide

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.260
a more predictive
framework for biology?

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:28.730
So is Earth the only
planet with life?

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.720
I guess the quick
answer is, I don't know.

00:10:31.720 --> 00:10:34.380
But as a biologist,
what I want to know

00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:37.910
is what is really unique
about life on Earth?

00:10:37.910 --> 00:10:40.100
Now, based on what we
know about life on Earth,

00:10:40.100 --> 00:10:43.840
if we found life
elsewhere, what is

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:46.060
our best guess or best
prediction in terms

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.010
of what would it be like?

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:49.880
And if we could
then have some sort

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:53.227
of prediction, what would those
predictions then be for life?

00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:58.240
So what I would like
to do in this talk

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:02.540
is counter two different views
about biology and arguably

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:05.480
about life in the universe.

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:09.232
But is life on Earth
really dictated by chance

00:11:09.232 --> 00:11:10.190
or is it deterministic?

00:11:13.420 --> 00:11:16.990
Now, in studying biology
for quite some time, what

00:11:16.990 --> 00:11:19.100
I'm actually impressed
with is that I

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:23.020
think there's a very big
division within biology.

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:25.770
Well, maybe division
is too harsh of a word.

00:11:25.770 --> 00:11:28.840
But it seems that biology really
does struggle with these two

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:31.580
different worldviews on life.

00:11:31.580 --> 00:11:35.920
In particular, is
life due to chance,

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:38.900
or is life deterministic?

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:40.490
So on the one
hand, life on Earth

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:43.700
is amazing and
intricate and diverse,

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:46.430
but the thinking goes
that it's actually

00:11:46.430 --> 00:11:49.910
arisen due to
multiple events that

00:11:49.910 --> 00:11:52.580
are essentially unpredictable.

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:55.460
On the other hand, we
could also make arguments

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:58.510
that life on Earth is
highly deterministic,

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:00.690
and that we can
ultimately boil things

00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:03.770
down to general rules and
principles which have guided

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:05.238
the diversification of life.

00:12:08.326 --> 00:12:09.200
So what about chance?

00:12:13.690 --> 00:12:16.280
So when we step back and
we look at the world,

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:19.720
and actually this is one
of my favorite paintings

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:21.240
I should say, by Jan Brueghel.

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:24.440
This is an 1613, Noah's Ark.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:26.600
When we step back and look
at the diversity of life

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:29.980
on the planet, it
really is amazing.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:31.310
There are small organisms.

00:12:31.310 --> 00:12:32.520
There's big organisms.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:34.400
There's organisms
that fly, organisms

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:36.190
that burrow in the earth.

00:12:36.190 --> 00:12:38.470
All the way from
microbes all the way up

00:12:38.470 --> 00:12:40.480
to the macroscopic,
huge organisms

00:12:40.480 --> 00:12:42.567
that we share the planet with.

00:12:42.567 --> 00:12:43.650
And it's actually amazing.

00:12:43.650 --> 00:12:45.550
If you study
biological processes,

00:12:45.550 --> 00:12:49.340
biological processes operate
at the subcellular scale,

00:12:49.340 --> 00:12:52.600
all the way up to the
scale of the biosphere.

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:56.270
So basically, life
operates over 21 orders

00:12:56.270 --> 00:12:59.010
of magnitude in scale.

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:00.460
So that's a number,
take a number

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:02.920
and move the decimal
point 21 times,

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:07.630
that's a huge range that
biology is operating over.

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:09.435
But is it all really by chance?

00:13:13.070 --> 00:13:15.820
So when I graduated from high
school and went to college,

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:18.410
I decided that I want to
be a biologist, because I

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:22.200
loved various organisms, I loved
the diversity of the Earth.

00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:24.350
I love going out
and understanding

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:26.270
how living things worked.

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:29.710
When I decided to
be a biology major,

00:13:29.710 --> 00:13:33.610
my parents gave me a book,
and it was this book.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:35.560
This is a book by Stephen
Jay Gould entitled

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:37.700
Wonderful Life,
The Burgess Shale

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:40.027
and the Nature of History.

00:13:40.027 --> 00:13:41.610
And what's interesting
about this book

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:44.750
is that it really struck
a chord in me early on.

00:13:44.750 --> 00:13:46.530
And I kind of assumed
that well, this

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:48.783
is how in general all
biologists really think.

00:13:48.783 --> 00:13:52.940
But it also kind of haunted
me, because it spelled

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:58.660
out a view of the world that,
if true, from my perspective,

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:00.380
can't be correct.

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:04.020
How can it be that all of life
and the diversity that we see

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:08.470
today is due just to chance?

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:10.630
So according to
Gould, chance was

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:14.110
and is one of the decisive
factors in the evolution

00:14:14.110 --> 00:14:16.450
of life on Earth.

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:20.200
And the paths then, that life
has taken since essentially,

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:24.130
life arose at the beginning
and evolved then, continuously

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:26.760
to today, these
various paths then

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:29.500
were actually constrained
by various historical events

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.770
well outside of the control
of anything biological.

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:35.930
Effectively, these
random historical events

00:14:35.930 --> 00:14:36.555
and accidents.

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:42.399
So that was in 1989.

00:14:42.399 --> 00:14:43.940
Now, what's interesting
is that Gould

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:47.370
takes a very interesting picture
about how the world actually

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:48.910
works.

00:14:48.910 --> 00:14:51.880
And within that
book, he actually

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:55.090
asked the reader to do
a thought experiment.

00:14:55.090 --> 00:15:02.630
In particular, if we were to
take the long history of life,

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:05.680
all the way from present
day all the way back

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:11.590
to 3.5 billion years ago,
the estimated origin of life,

00:15:11.590 --> 00:15:15.440
if we redid evolution,
that is if we replayed

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:19.440
the tape of life-- in
putting this together,

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:22.490
I was thinking about
my kids and trying

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:25.000
to explain to them this thought
experiment about rewinding

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:25.590
the tape.

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:29.320
And I was like, oh, yes, they
don't have tapes anymore.

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:37.160
So this is a dated analogy.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.880
But anyways, if we rewind the
tape, go back to the beginning

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:45.470
and play the play
of evolution again,

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:48.880
would we get the same
thing in the end?

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:51.450
So that was the
thought experiment.

00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:53.610
So what if we could
go back in time,

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:56.760
and what if we could watch
evolution happen again?

00:15:56.760 --> 00:15:58.130
What would it be like?

00:15:58.130 --> 00:16:00.300
So Gould in particular
focused on a period

00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:06.830
of time in the Cambrian
here, 541 million years ago.

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:09.680
I'm sorry, going
to the Precambrian.

00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:11.500
So during this time,
this was essentially

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.500
then, the biological
equivalent of the Big Bang.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:17.424
During this time,
the diversity of life

00:16:17.424 --> 00:16:19.840
really exploded, and we see
all of these various different

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:20.808
forms of life.

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:27.610
So Gould focused on one example,
in particular the organisms

00:16:27.610 --> 00:16:31.570
and the animals then found
then within the Burgess Shale.

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:34.170
The Burgess Shale then stems
from the middle Cambrian,

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:36.100
it's about 505
million years old.

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:38.670
It's perhaps one of the
most famous fossil beds

00:16:38.670 --> 00:16:39.670
in the world.

00:16:39.670 --> 00:16:42.810
The Burgess Shale is located
here in Alberta, Canada,

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:44.040
it's in the Canadian Rockies.

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:46.690
And so you can go
here and sample,

00:16:46.690 --> 00:16:49.880
and you get these amazing
well preserved fossils.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:53.210
These fossils preserved
soft parts then of the body.

00:16:53.210 --> 00:16:55.190
And you can go through
and you can really

00:16:55.190 --> 00:16:59.670
get a really good snapshot
of essentially a whole living

00:16:59.670 --> 00:17:02.790
ecosystem, all the various
different organisms then

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:04.230
that lived during that time.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:13.880
So during this time, life really
was a bizarre and alien world.

00:17:13.880 --> 00:17:16.530
If we were able to time
travel and go back and look

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:19.190
at these various different
organisms, many of us

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:21.660
would think that we
were in an alien world.

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:24.960
They look very different to
anything that we have today.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:32.220
The name of this organism,
this is Hallucinogenia,

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:37.640
mainly because it perplexed
people quite a bit.

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.200
We're not sure exactly
what it looked like.

00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:42.620
But over time, as more and
more fossils were found,

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:45.650
they're able to get a really
good kind of construction,

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:48.750
kind of an idea, a mental idea
of what this organism actually

00:17:48.750 --> 00:17:50.240
looked like.

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:53.200
And so the first then
drawings then of the organism

00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:56.240
looked something
like this, bizarre.

00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:58.710
Well, then that caused quite
a bit of debate and stir.

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:01.640
More fossils were found, and
they decided, well, actually,

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:04.690
they drew this upside down.

00:18:07.392 --> 00:18:08.850
So this interesting
little critter,

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:11.410
instead of having these
little spines as legs actually

00:18:11.410 --> 00:18:13.700
had these spines on the back.

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.890
And now the thinking is that
these are actual predator

00:18:16.890 --> 00:18:19.560
avoidance spines, effectively.

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:21.650
So when you see something
like that today,

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:25.970
it basically means, don't
eat me, don't touch me right.

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:27.470
Which is interesting,
because now we

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:30.350
can start to read into the
ecology of what that world was

00:18:30.350 --> 00:18:34.120
like, going all the way back
about 500 million years ago.

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:40.810
So these organisms were
quite bizarre and alien.

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:43.940
And the more we know, the more
bizarre and alien they look.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:47.000
But what's interesting is that
they were really only just

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.780
a lucky few of these organisms
during this time that actually

00:18:50.780 --> 00:18:54.680
made it through,
left descendants

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:58.640
that today partially
helped fill our world.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:01.590
So over the course of
history, chance alone wiped

00:19:01.590 --> 00:19:04.720
out many of these groups,
they're now extinct,

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:05.910
they're no longer with us.

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:09.363
So chance.

00:19:12.750 --> 00:19:15.890
So you don't have to go very
far back in recent biology

00:19:15.890 --> 00:19:18.470
to find some pretty
prominent thinkers in biology

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:22.320
arguing that chance and
unpredictability is a very

00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:24.930
central component of biology.

00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:29.310
So this is Watson and Crick,
co-discoverers of the structure

00:19:29.310 --> 00:19:30.145
and shape of DNA.

00:19:32.830 --> 00:19:37.420
In 1981, Crick then wrote
a book, Life Itself,

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:38.540
Its Origin in Nature.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:42.120
And so he has this great quote
in terms of the origin of life.

00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:43.760
And so he says here,
the origin of life

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:47.990
appears at the moment
to be almost a miracle.

00:19:47.990 --> 00:19:50.240
Effectively, punting the ball.

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:51.880
I don't know.

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:53.748
We've got DNA,
that's enough, right?

00:19:57.465 --> 00:20:00.910
Here's Jacques Monod or Monod.

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:05.170
Life is only the
result of pure chance.

00:20:05.170 --> 00:20:08.880
So the biosphere doesn't
contain any kind of set or class

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:12.190
of predictable objects, chance.

00:20:15.550 --> 00:20:20.160
So does life really come
down to a roll of the dice?

00:20:26.010 --> 00:20:29.830
Well, like anything in
biology, to make sense

00:20:29.830 --> 00:20:32.620
of not only the organisms
today but also of organisms

00:20:32.620 --> 00:20:37.310
in the past and the
origin of life in general,

00:20:37.310 --> 00:20:40.800
we ultimately have to understand
the unique selective pressures

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:45.670
of different environments
but also how life evolves.

00:20:45.670 --> 00:20:49.650
So this is Dobzhansky, he was
one of the main architects

00:20:49.650 --> 00:20:51.710
of modern evolutionary
theory in terms

00:20:51.710 --> 00:20:54.610
of our modern understanding
and our modern underpinning

00:20:54.610 --> 00:20:57.240
of the role of evolution
within biology.

00:20:57.240 --> 00:21:00.800
And he has this fantastic quote
that says, nothing in biology,

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:04.390
underscore nothing, makes
sense except in the light

00:21:04.390 --> 00:21:07.410
of evolution.

00:21:07.410 --> 00:21:09.623
So what about
evolution and chance?

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:15.730
So 1859, Charles
Darwin publishes

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:16.690
The Origin of Species.

00:21:19.330 --> 00:21:22.730
And so chance is actually
an important component

00:21:22.730 --> 00:21:26.440
of evolution by
natural selection.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:30.010
Now, what's interesting is I
have here Darwin's algorithm.

00:21:30.010 --> 00:21:33.710
And I do that because, if
you read the last paragraph

00:21:33.710 --> 00:21:36.200
in The Origin of
Species, Darwin actually

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:37.900
outlines then the
theory of evolution

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.950
by natural selection
as an algorithm.

00:21:40.950 --> 00:21:44.780
You can almost think of
this as a computer program.

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:48.960
So if a few truths are
correct, then the end result

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:52.090
must be true, and that
is natural selection.

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:55.150
Now, there is going to be
a quiz on this later on.

00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:56.980
So please take some notes.

00:21:56.980 --> 00:21:59.840
And I actually ask my
students, incoming students,

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:03.620
if they can basically
outline Darwin's algorithm.

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:06.110
I do that in the
start of every class.

00:22:06.110 --> 00:22:09.800
And none of them have gotten
it right at the start,

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:12.640
but they get it right
at the end of course.

00:22:12.640 --> 00:22:14.670
So what's the algorithm?

00:22:14.670 --> 00:22:19.950
Well, Darwin observed that
organisms or any organism

00:22:19.950 --> 00:22:24.210
has the propensity to ultimately
grow in its population size

00:22:24.210 --> 00:22:25.930
exponentially.

00:22:25.930 --> 00:22:30.450
So take this very cute example
of a bunch of ducks on a pond.

00:22:30.450 --> 00:22:34.430
Given enough time, we're
going to be not only filling

00:22:34.430 --> 00:22:39.240
the pond with ducks, but
very quickly, that population

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:41.900
is going to be
growing exponentially.

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:47.970
Any population, bacteria, ducks,
elephants, given enough time,

00:22:47.970 --> 00:22:49.890
that population
rate of growth is

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:51.590
going to be growing
exponentially

00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:56.230
to the point where it could be
growing at the speed of light.

00:22:56.230 --> 00:23:01.100
Imagine populations of elephants
growing at the speed of light,

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:04.730
clearly that's impossible.

00:23:04.730 --> 00:23:06.230
So this is the
insight of Darwin.

00:23:06.230 --> 00:23:10.570
Then he said, OK, if that's
true and all these individuals

00:23:10.570 --> 00:23:12.882
at some point are
going to be competing,

00:23:12.882 --> 00:23:18.780
competing either for
mates, space, resources,

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:22.330
that at some point, because of
this competition for limited

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:29.240
resources, that exponential
growth has to change.

00:23:29.240 --> 00:23:30.990
There's a leveling
off, there's a carrying

00:23:30.990 --> 00:23:33.239
capacity or a limit to
the number of individuals

00:23:33.239 --> 00:23:34.280
and that you can support.

00:23:38.770 --> 00:23:40.620
And this is his other insight.

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:43.630
If you look then within any
population, when organisms

00:23:43.630 --> 00:23:46.140
are than competing then
for limiting resources,

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:49.280
offspring are going to
differ in their ability then

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:52.110
to compete and obtain resources.

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:55.190
So some individuals are better
in terms of finding mates,

00:23:55.190 --> 00:23:56.250
competing for resources.

00:23:59.620 --> 00:24:01.750
Now we know that that
variation is ultimately

00:24:01.750 --> 00:24:07.140
due to genetic
variation, ultimately

00:24:07.140 --> 00:24:11.230
random mutation, chance events
introducing this variation then

00:24:11.230 --> 00:24:13.410
into the population.

00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:19.920
So according to Darwin, if
and all these things are true

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:23.240
and that genetic
variation is heritable,

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:26.780
then, given all of
the above, you're

00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:28.910
going to see
differential survivorship

00:24:28.910 --> 00:24:30.520
and/or reproduction.

00:24:30.520 --> 00:24:34.130
Some individuals will
survive better as well as

00:24:34.130 --> 00:24:38.490
reproduce better, some
combination of the two,

00:24:38.490 --> 00:24:41.180
because of which the population
phenotype of the genotype

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:43.040
will then change.

00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:47.445
But then the last step, go back
to one, and repeat infinitely.

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:51.890
So that was Darwin's insight.

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:54.940
So I want to emphasize here
that chance events enters

00:24:54.940 --> 00:25:01.180
in terms of how variation is
entered into the population.

00:25:01.180 --> 00:25:03.880
But I also want you to note
that individuals are competing

00:25:03.880 --> 00:25:07.130
for limited resources that
ultimately, then they're using

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:08.365
to fuel then their bodies.

00:25:12.280 --> 00:25:16.590
This is the end result.
This is the tree of life.

00:25:16.590 --> 00:25:21.130
So what I'm showing you here
at the base then of this plot,

00:25:21.130 --> 00:25:23.240
this is time going out
in either direction.

00:25:23.240 --> 00:25:26.400
So this is the birth of
the earth then going out

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:28.230
all the way into present day.

00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:30.670
So present day then is
the tips of the trees

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:35.140
all the way at the top, ranging
from bacteria, eukaryotes,

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:39.900
plants, fungi, all these
invertebrates, sharks and fish,

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:44.610
amphibians, reptiles, birds, and
mammals, very impressive sweep.

00:25:44.610 --> 00:25:47.270
So what's beautiful about
Darwin's insight is that all

00:25:47.270 --> 00:25:50.560
of the organisms today,
all that we know,

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:55.330
all can be traced back
to one common ancestor.

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:57.739
That ancestor then
left behind descendants

00:25:57.739 --> 00:25:59.530
who left behind
descendants that ultimately

00:25:59.530 --> 00:26:04.060
survived to today, populating
the world that we live in.

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:06.440
Now, I want to point out
several very interesting things

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:07.920
about this plot.

00:26:07.920 --> 00:26:09.890
If you'll notice, it's
kind of like an onion.

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:12.750
There's these different kind
of circles in there, right?

00:26:12.750 --> 00:26:16.350
These onions are actually
marking some very important

00:26:16.350 --> 00:26:18.350
Earth history events.

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:23.530
In particular, here is
the Cambrian Explosion,

00:26:23.530 --> 00:26:25.910
where all of these different
body plans and body types

00:26:25.910 --> 00:26:26.720
come about.

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:29.770
If you follow any one branch,
most of those branches

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:32.850
actually end.

00:26:32.850 --> 00:26:35.710
The ending then the branches
then is an extinction event.

00:26:35.710 --> 00:26:38.640
But if you'll notice, there's
some pretty large extinction

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:40.560
events.

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:42.760
There have been five
mass extinction events

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:49.020
on the earth, because of
which, on the order of 90%

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:54.340
to approximately 99% of all
species that have ever lived

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:58.540
on the planet are now extinct.

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:00.210
So literally, we are the 1%.

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:09.410
So chance events.

00:27:09.410 --> 00:27:11.010
Many of these mass
extinctions are now

00:27:11.010 --> 00:27:15.130
pointing back to, just by
chance, a large asteroid hit.

00:27:15.130 --> 00:27:19.810
So 65 million years ago,
there was a very large one

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:23.690
that wiped out quite a
bit of life on Earth.

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:26.160
But also 65 million
years ago, also ushered

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:36.490
in a new group of organisms who
before were relatively rare.

00:27:36.490 --> 00:27:39.930
So this extinction event ushered
in the age of the mammals

00:27:39.930 --> 00:27:41.690
and the extinction
of the dinosaurs.

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:45.810
And it also ushered in
a very interesting niche

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:49.450
art of extinction
events on the internet.

00:27:49.450 --> 00:27:53.320
And I have to say that these
are all very bad pieces of art.

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.730
I wouldn't want to
put these on my wall,

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:58.441
but somebody spent a lot
of time in designing these.

00:28:04.570 --> 00:28:06.200
Maybe you saw this recent study.

00:28:06.200 --> 00:28:09.130
So this came out
just a few weeks ago.

00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:13.930
This was in the New York
Times, a very large study

00:28:13.930 --> 00:28:17.180
on risk of cancer.

00:28:17.180 --> 00:28:23.240
What they find is that random
mutations, chance events,

00:28:23.240 --> 00:28:29.510
account for about 2/3 of
the risk of getting cancer,

00:28:29.510 --> 00:28:33.180
which leaves the other
suspects, heredity,

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:35.710
environmental
factors, accounting

00:28:35.710 --> 00:28:41.190
for a very small fraction of
your risk of getting cancer,

00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:41.850
chance events.

00:28:45.230 --> 00:28:50.960
So two fundamentally
different views of biology.

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:54.198
Chance, but now let's
talk about determinism.

00:28:56.950 --> 00:28:59.350
Is life on Earth organized
by a set of general rules

00:28:59.350 --> 00:29:00.855
and principles?

00:29:00.855 --> 00:29:02.480
The thinking here is
that, well, maybe,

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:07.400
the winners and the
losers may change,

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:09.684
but the rules of the game
have stayed the same.

00:29:12.350 --> 00:29:13.748
And if true, what are the rules?

00:29:16.820 --> 00:29:18.770
Another book that
I was influenced

00:29:18.770 --> 00:29:21.870
by in graduate school
was actually a book

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:25.710
by Harold Morowitz
published in 1970.

00:29:25.710 --> 00:29:27.210
And so what we can
ask are, what are

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:28.970
the general aspects of life?

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:32.280
So if we went back and replayed
the tape of life again,

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:35.180
would we likely see
biological constants,

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:37.355
things that repeatedly evolve?

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:41.790
So Morowtiz has a great quote.

00:29:41.790 --> 00:29:45.450
The energy that flows
through any sort of system

00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:47.550
ultimately organizes
that system.

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:50.020
So he was think of
physical systems,

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:51.632
but also biology
is no different.

00:29:54.590 --> 00:29:56.030
Biology ultimately does work.

00:29:56.030 --> 00:30:00.840
Biology consumes resources,
converts then those resources

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:02.780
into offspring, and does work.

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:05.880
We can think of biology as also
having a very physical work

00:30:05.880 --> 00:30:08.110
component.

00:30:08.110 --> 00:30:09.770
So here's the hypothesis.

