a lot of fractal structures

00:46:48.190 --> 00:46:52.750
that have mathematically
very similar properties

00:46:52.750 --> 00:46:54.550
for many different
functions that

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:57.930
have evolved multiple
times that are effectively

00:46:57.930 --> 00:47:00.730
identical to each other.

00:47:00.730 --> 00:47:01.870
So you're a great example.

00:47:01.870 --> 00:47:04.450
If I boiled away your skin
and looked in your body,

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:06.639
you'd look like this.

00:47:06.639 --> 00:47:07.555
You're a sitting tree.

00:47:10.620 --> 00:47:12.710
Leaf veins.

00:47:12.710 --> 00:47:14.860
Leaves are nice and green,
but if you take away

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:17.330
that outer skin,
they're beautiful,

00:47:17.330 --> 00:47:20.830
and this is what
you're left with.

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:23.100
Your lungs.

00:47:23.100 --> 00:47:24.890
This could be a root
system, it could

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:29.540
be a branching architecture
of a tropical tree.

00:47:29.540 --> 00:47:34.170
Within your brain,
information networks,

00:47:34.170 --> 00:47:36.130
these transport
electrical signals for

00:47:36.130 --> 00:47:38.470
not only your motor control
but also your learning

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:40.876
and your sensory perception.

00:47:40.876 --> 00:47:42.250
What's interesting
is that we can

00:47:42.250 --> 00:47:44.390
describe all of these
different networks

00:47:44.390 --> 00:47:47.330
and find that they have very
similar mathematical signals

00:47:47.330 --> 00:47:50.405
associated with them.

00:47:50.405 --> 00:47:51.970
Here's an aquatic example.

00:47:51.970 --> 00:47:54.320
This is a modern filter feeder.

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:59.960
This a gorgonian in a coral
reef, And this is a fun one.

00:47:59.960 --> 00:48:02.530
So let's go back to
the Burgess Shale.

00:48:02.530 --> 00:48:06.830
So they think that this
organism, it's a fossil,

00:48:06.830 --> 00:48:11.890
was some sort of an alga,
some algae of some sort.

00:48:11.890 --> 00:48:13.710
It's now extinct.

00:48:13.710 --> 00:48:17.540
But what's very interesting
is that if we analyze

00:48:17.540 --> 00:48:20.724
the branching structure
of these organisms,

00:48:20.724 --> 00:48:22.390
you'd be hard pressed
to tell this apart

00:48:22.390 --> 00:48:26.470
from a lung or a tree,
oak tree, that you'd

00:48:26.470 --> 00:48:27.660
find growing in your yard.

00:48:31.460 --> 00:48:35.490
So why these treelike networks?

00:48:35.490 --> 00:48:37.100
So one of the projects
that I decided

00:48:37.100 --> 00:48:39.570
to focus on when I
was in graduate school

00:48:39.570 --> 00:48:41.820
was essentially
asking this question.

00:48:41.820 --> 00:48:45.540
Why is it that we tend to see
these branching morphologies

00:48:45.540 --> 00:48:47.300
throughout most of biology?

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:49.350
It doesn't matter if
you're a plant or an animal

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:51.310
or even within a
cell, we tend to see

00:48:51.310 --> 00:48:54.020
these sorts of structures.

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:55.550
So here's the argument.

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:58.320
So evolution by
natural selection

00:48:58.320 --> 00:49:04.100
actually favors this sort of
network, because it's optimal.

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:07.680
And we would expect to see these
networks anytime in biology

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:12.170
where resources are limiting and
where competition or limiting

00:49:12.170 --> 00:49:13.990
resources is keen.

00:49:13.990 --> 00:49:17.510
Because these networks, they
tend to be space filling,

00:49:17.510 --> 00:49:20.100
they fill some sort of space.

00:49:20.100 --> 00:49:22.930
But what's also interesting
is that-- here's

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:27.800
a little bit of lingo-- they
tend to be area preserving.

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:31.330
And these are just fancy ways of
saying that, by space filling,

00:49:31.330 --> 00:49:35.040
these networks maximize
resource exchange surfaces.

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:38.790
Organisms are exchanging
resources from the environment

00:49:38.790 --> 00:49:41.820
into their body, and
they're transporting

00:49:41.820 --> 00:49:43.990
within their body
or their cells,

00:49:43.990 --> 00:49:45.400
ultimately to fuel metabolism.

00:49:47.930 --> 00:49:51.080
These networks are also
designed so that they

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:53.590
minimize transport costs.

00:49:53.590 --> 00:49:54.980
So you can boil this down.

00:49:54.980 --> 00:49:58.100
These networks give you the
biggest bang for the buck.

00:49:58.100 --> 00:50:01.200
You can take in a bunch of
resources or information,

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:03.540
transport them within
the body to fuel

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:06.780
all of your central nervous
system or your metabolism

00:50:06.780 --> 00:50:07.888
at a minimum cost.

00:50:10.700 --> 00:50:14.590
So the result then are networks
that maximize energy throughput

00:50:14.590 --> 00:50:15.614
at a minimum cost.

00:50:19.010 --> 00:50:21.730
We're in the homestretch here.

00:50:21.730 --> 00:50:23.970
Last part.

00:50:23.970 --> 00:50:29.410
Life is characterized by
a set of scaling laws.

00:50:29.410 --> 00:50:33.420
And as a result, and this
is really interesting,

00:50:33.420 --> 00:50:38.720
the rate of aging is
actually scaled in a way

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:40.890
so that all of life
actually fluxes

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:43.530
about the same amount
of energy per unit mass

00:50:43.530 --> 00:50:45.790
across all living things.

00:50:45.790 --> 00:50:46.900
And they say, my goodness.

00:50:46.900 --> 00:50:49.720
That sounds really
quite remarkable.

00:50:49.720 --> 00:50:51.960
But I would like you to
consider for a moment

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:55.050
these wonderful and
amazing organisms.

00:50:55.050 --> 00:50:57.770
They do very different things.

00:50:57.770 --> 00:51:00.420
They feed on
different resources.

00:51:00.420 --> 00:51:04.232
Some of them live a short
time, others live a long time.

00:51:07.440 --> 00:51:09.565
So what I'm to do is only
take all those organisms,

00:51:09.565 --> 00:51:13.330
and I'm going to
put them on a graph.

00:51:13.330 --> 00:51:16.390
So at the bottom, I have
their body size or their mass.

00:51:16.390 --> 00:51:19.870
You pick them up, you weigh
them, you put them on a scale.

00:51:19.870 --> 00:51:23.390
On the y-axis, I'm going to plot
a measure of how fast they're

00:51:23.390 --> 00:51:27.380
producing biomass, how
fast they're growing.

00:51:27.380 --> 00:51:30.590
So remember that growth
is fueled ultimately

00:51:30.590 --> 00:51:32.947
by the TCA cycle.

00:51:35.690 --> 00:51:42.930
So let's look at insects,
birds, fish, plants,

00:51:42.930 --> 00:51:50.080
unicellular all the way up to
multicellular plants, mammals,

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:54.680
protists, zooplankton.

00:51:54.680 --> 00:51:58.840
And what was really interesting
is that recently, we

00:51:58.840 --> 00:52:02.850
were wondering if we could
put long-extinct organisms

00:52:02.850 --> 00:52:04.860
on this plot.

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:09.770
And what's really interesting,
in the bones of dinosaurs,

00:52:09.770 --> 00:52:12.330
if you cut open their
bones and their fossils

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:14.230
and you look then
at the bones, what

00:52:14.230 --> 00:52:18.684
you'll actually find with things
that look like tree rings.

00:52:18.684 --> 00:52:20.350
So just like a tree
when you cut it down

00:52:20.350 --> 00:52:23.290
it has growth rings, a
lot of different organisms

00:52:23.290 --> 00:52:25.040
than that leave behind
bone, you can also

00:52:25.040 --> 00:52:26.123
measure their growth rate.

00:52:26.123 --> 00:52:31.060
If some basics of how
to convert that to mass,

00:52:31.060 --> 00:52:36.400
we have estimates of where
the dinosaurs would be,

00:52:36.400 --> 00:52:37.375
things long extinct.

00:52:40.282 --> 00:52:41.240
So this is interesting.

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:43.550
All organisms are
described, apparently,

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:48.410
by an approximate
general scaling function.

00:52:48.410 --> 00:52:53.587
As you go across scales of
size, we know how they grow.

00:52:56.720 --> 00:53:01.520
What's interesting
is that plot says

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:05.300
that the total amount of energy
a very small organism or a very

00:53:05.300 --> 00:53:11.930
big organism uses per unit
mass for their entire lifespan

00:53:11.930 --> 00:53:15.000
is approximately the same.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:21.154
It's actually 8 times 10 to the
fifth kilojoules per kilogram.

00:53:21.154 --> 00:53:23.320
So this is like the Hitchhikers
Guide to the Galaxy.

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:26.040
Why that number?

00:53:26.040 --> 00:53:31.550
I have no idea, but it exists.

00:53:34.510 --> 00:53:38.210
Within a mouse, the TCA cycle
is spinning very rapidly.

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:40.420
Within an elephant,
it spins very slowly.

00:53:44.390 --> 00:53:48.050
An interesting outcome
of that, if you calculate

00:53:48.050 --> 00:53:50.340
the total number of
heartbeats in a mammal,

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:55.020
you can do this for birds too or
anything with a heart-- plants

00:53:55.020 --> 00:53:57.150
don't have hearts,
there are actually

00:53:57.150 --> 00:54:00.342
very similar numbers for them
but for different quantities.

00:54:00.342 --> 00:54:02.050
If you actually plot
out the total number

00:54:02.050 --> 00:54:04.920
of heartbeats across
all the mammals,

00:54:04.920 --> 00:54:07.010
there's some variability.

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:11.090
But it's about 7.3 plus or minus
5.6 times 10 to the eighth,

00:54:11.090 --> 00:54:13.610
about a billion.

00:54:13.610 --> 00:54:16.160
Now, I'm sure some of you,
quantitatively astute,

00:54:16.160 --> 00:54:17.810
have probably
calculated your number

00:54:17.810 --> 00:54:20.361
and found that you
well exceed a billion.

00:54:23.010 --> 00:54:28.136
That's all right, there is
some slop in these numbers.

00:54:28.136 --> 00:54:29.510
I'm sure you're
going to be fine.

00:54:35.430 --> 00:54:36.850
But this is what's interesting.

00:54:36.850 --> 00:54:38.940
Why is it about a billion?

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:40.500
Why isn't it 100?

00:54:40.500 --> 00:54:42.260
Why isn't it a million?

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:43.320
Why isn't it a trillion?

00:54:43.320 --> 00:54:46.290
Why that number?

00:54:46.290 --> 00:54:48.527
Well, probably, it ultimately
has to do with the fact

00:54:48.527 --> 00:54:50.610
that-- you can just think
of any car that you buy.

00:54:50.610 --> 00:54:55.910
At some point, it's going
to wear out, entropy.

00:54:55.910 --> 00:54:58.390
But what's interesting
is that we don't really

00:54:58.390 --> 00:55:00.630
have a really good
biological understanding

00:55:00.630 --> 00:55:01.890
for why these numbers.

00:55:05.370 --> 00:55:07.603
Last thing that I'm going
to end on, ecosystems.

00:55:10.782 --> 00:55:12.240
So if you think
about an ecosystem,

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:16.840
you can have a trophic
network, that is who eats who.

00:55:16.840 --> 00:55:21.310
So you can have plants,
herbivores eat the plants,

00:55:21.310 --> 00:55:23.610
larger carnivores
eat the herbivores,

00:55:23.610 --> 00:55:26.400
you have secondary carnivores,
tertiary carnivores,

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:28.590
carnivores eating carnivores.

00:55:28.590 --> 00:55:30.760
It gets really messy.

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:36.250
Now, if you think about an
ecosystem, that dissipation

00:55:36.250 --> 00:55:40.130
of energy, either from
the deep sea vents

00:55:40.130 --> 00:55:42.540
or from photosynthesis
from the sun,

00:55:42.540 --> 00:55:44.420
is dissipated then
through the biosphere

00:55:44.420 --> 00:55:47.890
through these trophic
interactions of who eats who.

00:55:47.890 --> 00:55:52.620
But remember, that energy is
all being paced and scaled

00:55:52.620 --> 00:55:55.400
ultimately by what's happening
not only in your mitochondria

00:55:55.400 --> 00:56:00.780
but also down to the core
metabolism of the TCA cycle.

00:56:00.780 --> 00:56:04.137
So we can talk about
ecosystem-scale metabolism.

00:56:04.137 --> 00:56:06.220
We can talk about the
metabolism of the biosphere.

00:56:09.887 --> 00:56:11.470
So what I'm showing
you here actually,

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:15.340
this is some work led in
part by Neil Martinez.

00:56:15.340 --> 00:56:16.950
Neil is one of my
colleagues here

00:56:16.950 --> 00:56:18.854
at the University of Arizona.

00:56:18.854 --> 00:56:20.520
And Neil and his
colleagues went through

00:56:20.520 --> 00:56:22.880
and they did a fantastic study.

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:27.880
So they looked at these
networks of interactions.

00:56:27.880 --> 00:56:31.380
So you can kind of think of this
as any other kind of network

00:56:31.380 --> 00:56:33.650
of interactions, like on
Facebook or the internet,

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:35.500
kind of like who's
connected to who.

00:56:35.500 --> 00:56:37.000
But here, what we're
doing is, we're

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:41.190
looking at a trophic network in
terms of having the plants here

00:56:41.190 --> 00:56:44.350
at the bottom, then the
herbivores, who eats who

00:56:44.350 --> 00:56:47.300
in terms of which herbivores
are on which plants but also

00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:51.985
the top carnivores here in
terms of who are they eating.

00:56:51.985 --> 00:56:53.610
So what's actually
very interesting is,

00:56:53.610 --> 00:56:56.690
I'm showing you two of these
different trophic networks

00:56:56.690 --> 00:56:59.600
or food webs.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:01.400
One of them is from
the Burgess Shale.

00:57:04.380 --> 00:57:07.070
The other is from a lake,
probably in Wisconsin.

00:57:11.450 --> 00:57:14.250
Now, what's interesting
is that statistically,

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:16.870
you can analyze than the
degree of connectedness

00:57:16.870 --> 00:57:18.260
then of this network.

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:23.420
And in general, you can't tell
them apart from each other.

00:57:23.420 --> 00:57:26.600
Their network of
interactions are organized

00:57:26.600 --> 00:57:28.679
in a very similar way.

00:57:28.679 --> 00:57:30.720
So when we look at these
networks of interactions

00:57:30.720 --> 00:57:33.880
remember, we're seeing the
dissipation of metabolic energy

00:57:33.880 --> 00:57:36.170
throughout the ecosystem.

00:57:36.170 --> 00:57:41.040
And those interactions
are organized in a way

00:57:41.040 --> 00:57:43.550
so that metabolism
is then passed

00:57:43.550 --> 00:57:45.231
through all the
way from herbivores

00:57:45.231 --> 00:57:46.105
up to the carnivores.

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:56.970
So what I'm showing
you here is one view

00:57:56.970 --> 00:57:59.540
of the metabolism of the earth.

00:57:59.540 --> 00:58:02.720
This is carbon
assimilation, how much

00:58:02.720 --> 00:58:08.010
carbon is coming into
the terrestrial biosphere

00:58:08.010 --> 00:58:10.270
via photosynthesis.

00:58:10.270 --> 00:58:14.560
And this movie is looping
through at a monthly timestep,

00:58:14.560 --> 00:58:15.836
every month.

00:58:15.836 --> 00:58:17.460
And so if you watch
it, what you'll see

00:58:17.460 --> 00:58:20.310
is you'll see seasonalities
during the year.

00:58:20.310 --> 00:58:24.200
So the Northern Hemisphere
will green up in the summer,

00:58:24.200 --> 00:58:27.860
but when winter comes,
it'll brown down.

00:58:27.860 --> 00:58:30.710
You'll also see within the
tropics and South America

00:58:30.710 --> 00:58:32.020
and Australia and Asia.

00:58:32.020 --> 00:58:33.820
You'll see, even
within the tropics,

00:58:33.820 --> 00:58:36.970
the pulsing of
terrestrial metabolism

00:58:36.970 --> 00:58:38.545
to flux throughout the year.

00:58:41.072 --> 00:58:42.030
And you can watch this.

00:58:42.030 --> 00:58:44.330
This goes out actually, for
many, many different years.

00:58:44.330 --> 00:58:48.540
But this is variation
in ecosystem metabolism.

00:58:48.540 --> 00:58:50.890
Now, if you're interested,
we can talk about this later,

00:58:50.890 --> 00:58:53.500
but I don't have the time.

00:58:53.500 --> 00:58:56.880
But I will tell you
that you can take

00:58:56.880 --> 00:58:59.880
what we know of
core metabolism, you

00:58:59.880 --> 00:59:05.250
can take our knowledge of
how fast the TCA cycle spins,

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:07.600
you can take the different
sizes of organisms

00:59:07.600 --> 00:59:13.040
that we know exist to actually
predict the metabolism

00:59:13.040 --> 00:59:16.400
at the scale of an ecosystem.

00:59:16.400 --> 00:59:19.640
And we can trace that
metabolism all the way down

00:59:19.640 --> 00:59:21.910
to the core
metabolism ultimately

00:59:21.910 --> 00:59:24.960
down to the TCA cycle.

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:28.720
So the Earth is literally
a metabolizing entity,

00:59:28.720 --> 00:59:32.160
ultimately fueled by a
set of core reactions

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:36.190
that are ubiquitous
across all of life.

00:59:36.190 --> 00:59:38.910
And that dissipation of
energy, both within organisms

00:59:38.910 --> 00:59:42.300
and across ecosystems,
appears to also

00:59:42.300 --> 00:59:46.240
be governed by general rules
with how natural selection has

00:59:46.240 --> 00:59:49.030
maximized not only
distribution networks,

00:59:49.030 --> 00:59:52.120
but also control the
interactions of who eats who

00:59:52.120 --> 00:59:55.770
and how energy is dissipated.

00:59:55.770 --> 01:00:00.140
So to summarize,
general aspects of life.

01:00:00.140 --> 01:00:02.760
Life does work.

01:00:02.760 --> 01:00:05.880
Metabolism maintains
homeostasis.

01:00:05.880 --> 01:00:08.350
So right now, your body
is working very hard

01:00:08.350 --> 01:00:11.610
to maintain your core
temperature around a very

01:00:11.610 --> 01:00:13.850
small degree of fluctuation.

01:00:13.850 --> 01:00:17.450
Any deviation from
that is deadly.

01:00:17.450 --> 01:00:19.610
You spend a lot of
energy trying to maintain

01:00:19.610 --> 01:00:22.870
your core metabolism temperature
at a very constant level,

01:00:22.870 --> 01:00:25.650
homeostasis.

01:00:25.650 --> 01:00:28.280
Life in general evolves,
becoming increasingly larger

01:00:28.280 --> 01:00:29.440
and larger and larger.

01:00:29.440 --> 01:00:31.621
This doesn't mean that
small organisms disappear.

01:00:31.621 --> 01:00:33.870
There's plenty of different
places for small organisms

01:00:33.870 --> 01:00:34.690
to live.

01:00:34.690 --> 01:00:39.880
But larger organisms
effectively by becoming larger,

01:00:39.880 --> 01:00:42.250
they avoid the competition
from smaller ones

01:00:42.250 --> 01:00:45.045
but can exploit and dominate
more and more resources.

01:00:47.850 --> 01:00:49.377
Life uses fractal networks.

01:00:53.400 --> 01:00:55.430
They appear to
optimize transport

01:00:55.430 --> 01:00:58.060
in terms of time and flow.

01:00:58.060 --> 01:01:02.390
Again, natural selection appears
to be doing the optimization.

01:01:02.390 --> 01:01:06.320
Life itself is scaled
by core metabolism.

01:01:06.320 --> 01:01:08.683
This has remained constant
across all scales.

01:01:11.290 --> 01:01:15.680
But life's interactions in terms
of the struggle for resources

01:01:15.680 --> 01:01:20.740
to fuel metabolism is
ultimately scaled and paced

01:01:20.740 --> 01:01:24.900
by the core rate of
metabolic reactions.

01:01:24.900 --> 01:01:26.490
So in general, the
diversity of life

01:01:26.490 --> 01:01:29.586
is shaped by this flow
and dissipation of energy.

01:01:34.220 --> 01:01:37.080
So I started with this
dichotomy within biology

01:01:37.080 --> 01:01:40.930
that we have both a
deterministic and also

01:01:40.930 --> 01:01:44.340
a chance view on life.

01:01:44.340 --> 01:01:47.200
So determinism, there are
regular deterministic processes

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:50.750
that shape the diversity of
life, the laws of chemistry,

01:01:50.750 --> 01:01:55.030
physics, combined with
evolution by natural selection

01:01:55.030 --> 01:01:59.060
appears to be very general in
terms of many different aspects

01:01:59.060 --> 01:02:01.760
of life.

01:02:01.760 --> 01:02:03.870
Again, these rules appear
to ultimately determine

01:02:03.870 --> 01:02:07.720
not only the pace of life
but also the functioning

01:02:07.720 --> 01:02:10.180
of Earth's ecosystems.

01:02:10.180 --> 01:02:13.460
But we also know that there
is a big component of chance

01:02:13.460 --> 01:02:15.680
as well.

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:19.700
Random mutations are a key
component of evolution.

01:02:19.700 --> 01:02:22.235
Extinction at many levels
happened constantly.

01:02:24.810 --> 01:02:26.370
Because of these
extinction events,

01:02:26.370 --> 01:02:27.900
ecosystems undergo
rearrangements.

01:02:34.800 --> 01:02:36.920
So let's try to
put this together.

01:02:36.920 --> 01:02:44.470
Well, life in general is both
by chance and deterministic.

01:02:44.470 --> 01:02:48.230
Even though the players
of the game have changed,

01:02:48.230 --> 01:02:51.290
it looks as if there are
some general rules that

01:02:51.290 --> 01:02:54.090
have remained the same.

01:02:54.090 --> 01:02:58.440
And I've showed you five
general aspects of life

01:02:58.440 --> 01:03:02.520
on Earth which are
tantalizing and suggest

01:03:02.520 --> 01:03:05.270
that if we did find
life elsewhere,

01:03:05.270 --> 01:03:07.850
and if resources are limiting,
so there is competition

01:03:07.850 --> 01:03:10.520
for limiting space,
resources, or mates,

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:16.260
we may expect to see these
aspects of life repeated there.

01:03:16.260 --> 01:03:18.540
And so this is
interesting to ponder

01:03:18.540 --> 01:03:22.340
once we do start looking for
life in the next several talks,

01:03:22.340 --> 01:03:24.312
what that life may look like.

